    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-18T17:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-18T17:29:00-05:00" n="828"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d828">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/1748</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The War Trade Board Representative in Cuba</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MHH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-18T17:00:00-05:29">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 18, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9.24 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your August 21, 4 p.m., and my August 22. It is reported here that agreement has
                    been reached in Washington with Spanish lines to coal all their boats at Porto
                    Rico or other American ports to take effect on October 1. Please advise me if
                    this is correct.<note n="1" xml:id="d828fn1">Department’s memorandum attached to
                        this telegram reads: “Sept. 20, 1918. Mr. <persName
                            corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_FPj1">Fuller</persName> [of the War Trade
                        Board] telephoned to say that he was informed by Mr.
                            <persName>Richards</persName> [of the Board] that no such agreement had
                        been made but that the agent of the Pinillos Line had assured him that they
                        were quite prepared to have their ships stop at Porto Rico for censorship
                        purposes and that the line would undertake to do this without having the
                        matter taken up diplomatically. <persName>L[eland] H[arrison.]</persName>”
                        The telegram sent in reply, Sept. 20, merely stated “no such agreement has
                        been made.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MHH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morgan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
